think Checked the device's own real specs directly rather than assuming -- Google's own support page and GrapheneOS's own review/support material confirm Tensor G4, Titan M2, a 6.3" 120Hz pOLED, launched 20260305, full GrapheneOS production support with a self-install web installer (grapheneos.org/install/web, ~15-30 minutes), and an update runway to ~2033. Cross-checked the price against current new retail (~$450-550) to confirm $325 used is a genuinely good deal, not merely asserted as one.
think Held the new fact against the go-to-market brief's own already-written three-tier structure (active-designing/20260715-194500) rather than treating it as an isolated event -- the brief's own Value tier named a used Pixel 7a/8a (Tensor G2/G3, ~$150-250) as the destination reached last, after flagship lessons land. The Pixel 10a is a real, one-generation-newer instance of exactly that same device shape, landing ahead of the flagship purchase the brief's own ordering plans for. Named this precisely as the tier table's own ordering welcoming a device-in-hand rather than conflicting with the flagship-first strategy -- the plan does not need to change, only be updated with what is now real.
think Updated the honest register in both places that named "no physical Pixel owned yet" as of 20260716 (context/specs/two-dev-environments-and-mobile-emulation.md's own HAWM3 rung, and the go-to-market brief itself) -- careful to distinguish owning the device from HAWM3's own rung actually closing: the device satisfies HAWM3's gate, but the rung itself stays open until GrapheneOS is actually flashed onto it, which is Keaton's own next real, human step, not something this session did or could do.
obs This is the first real hardware fact the whole GrapheneOS/Pixel thread has had all session, after two full days of pure emulation work (HAWM0, HAWM1) -- worth naming plainly as a genuine turning point in the thread's own register, not just another dated bullet.
